        Sunlight appears white to our eyes, but it is actually a combination of all the colors in a rainbow. When this light travels through space, it passes freely without hitting anything. However, once it reaches Earth, it must pass through our atmosphere, which is filled with invisible gases like nitrogen and oxygen.

        As the sunlight moves through the air, it bumps into these gas molecules. This interaction causes the light to scatter, or spread out in every direction. The reason for this is that shorter waves, like blue and violet, scatter much more strongly than longer waves, like red and yellow. The blue light gets bounced around by the air molecules constantly, filling the sky with this color.

        Even though violet light scatters even more than blue, the sky does not look purple to us. This happens because our eyes are not very sensitive to violet light, and the sun produces less violet light than blue light. So, when the scattered light reaches our eyes, we see the blue color as the dominant one, making the sky appear blue to us.

